1. Describe your education and experience in transportation policy and planning.
I hold a Ph.D. in Geography from Kent State University and a Master of Arts in Geography from SUNY Binghamton, with academic training in transportation planning, GIS, spatial analysis, and quantitative modeling.

As a Sustainability Transportation Analyst with Caltrans' Director's Office of Sustainability, I independently develop analytical methodologies and decision-support frameworks that support statewide transportation planning, sustainability, equity, safety, and Vehicle Miles Traveled (VMT) reduction initiatives.

My work spans four major statewide initiatives. I lead development of the Transportation Equity Index (EQI) Maintenance Use Case by designing analytical methodologies, conducting statewide implementation analyses, and supporting equity-informed maintenance planning and resource allocation. I also develop EQI implementation guidance and analytical use cases that promote consistent integration of transportation equity into planning and investment decisions across Caltrans.

I currently lead the technical development of a statewide Speed Performance research initiative by creating analytical methodologies to identify excessive speeding and support future speed abatement planning aligned with the Caltrans Strategic Management Plan. I also developed the analytical methodology and technical documentation for the Corridor Prioritization Tool, creating a standardized decision-support framework aligned with the Caltrans Strategic Management Plan and CAPTI. In addition, I conduct before-and-after traffic volume analyses using StreetLight and Replica to evaluate transportation projects and support rural VMT reduction strategies.

These experiences have strengthened my ability to translate transportation policy objectives into practical analytical methodologies that support statewide planning and data-driven decision-making.
2. Describe your education and experience with data analysis in the transportation field, including GIS and statistical software.
I have extensive experience applying GIS, programming, and quantitative analysis to transportation planning using ArcGIS Pro, R, Python, SQL, Tableau, StreetLight, and Replica.

At Caltrans, I develop repeatable analytical workflows that integrate transportation, demographic, and spatial datasets into practical planning tools. My work includes developing GIS workflows, automating analyses in R, creating performance metrics, and producing maps, dashboards, technical reports, and decision-support products.

For the EQI Maintenance Use Case, I developed a GIS and R workflow integrating maintenance records, EQI data, demographic information, and operational performance measures. For the Speed Performance initiative, I developed statewide analytical methods and performance metrics to identify excessive speeding using traffic performance data. For the Corridor Prioritization Tool, I developed the analytical methodology and technical workflow used to evaluate multiple transportation performance indicators. I also analyzed historical traffic volumes using StreetLight and Replica to evaluate transportation project performance and support rural VMT reduction initiatives.

My experience enables me to transform complex transportation data into practical analytical methodologies that support planning, investment prioritization, and policy implementation across Caltrans.
3. Describe your experience with effective communication skills (email, Microsoft Teams, WebEx, phone, in person, etc.).
Effective communication is an essential part of my work because nearly every project requires collaboration across multiple Caltrans divisions and technical disciplines.

I regularly communicate with planners, engineers, GIS specialists, managers, and executive staff through email, Microsoft Teams, WebEx, phone calls, in-person meetings, technical reports, presentations, and user documentation. I routinely explain analytical methodologies, discuss technical approaches, incorporate stakeholder feedback, and communicate findings to both technical and non-technical audiences.

My work on EQI requires close collaboration with the Director's Office of Equity and Tribal Affairs to develop implementation strategies and analytical guidance. I also collaborate with the VMT Team on transportation project evaluations and authored the technical documentation for the Corridor Prioritization Tool to ensure consistent application of its analytical framework.

These experiences have strengthened my ability to communicate complex technical concepts clearly, collaborate across multidisciplinary teams, and support transportation planning through effective communication and technical leadership.
